  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Performing background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting cash transactions over certain thresholds\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Compliance Regulations\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Implementing Anti-Money Laundering (AML) programs\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n\n4. Training\n- Educating employees about money laundering risks\n- Implementing compliance training programs\n\n5. Internal Controls\n- Establishing robust compliance procedures\n- Creating audit trails\n- Implementing transaction monitoring systems\n\n6. Penalties for Non-Compliance\n- Potential significant financial fines\n- Potential criminal liability\n- Risk of losing banking licenses\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent criminal financial activities and ensure transparency in financial systems.",
